
It's a common cry from the public: "Why can't a government run like a business?" Well, Sandy Springs' first city manager will have to do just that, says a leader of the city management search team. The city-to-be has received about 50 r&eacute;sum&eacute;s from applicants for a job that will be unprecedented in Georgia and rare anywhere in the nation, said Bernard Kearse, co-chairman of the Sandy Springs Human Resources Task Force. 

